

🏎️ Arduino White-Line Follower
📖 Project Overview
This project is an autonomous robot built with an Arduino UNO R4 and an L298N Motor Driver.
It is specifically designed to follow a white line on a black surface using "inverted" infrared logic.

🛠️ Components Required
Arduino Uno (R3): The brain of the robot.
IR Reflection Sensors (x2): Detects line contrast via infrared light.

L298N Motor Driver: Acts as the power converter between the Arduino and the motors.

DC Gear Motors (x2): Provides the torque needed for movement.

2WD Smart Car Chassis: The structural frame.

Wheels & Caster: Two drive wheels and one pivot wheel for steering.

Dual Power Supply: 9V battery for logic; 4x AA batteries for motor power.


🔌 Pin Mapping
Component	Arduino Pin	Connection Note
Left IR Sensor	Pin 2	Signal Output
Right IR Sensor	Pin 3	Signal Output
Left Motor (IN1)	Pin 5	L298N Input
Left Motor (IN2)	Pin 6	L298N Input
Right Motor (IN3)	Pin 9	L298N Input
Right Motor (IN4)	Pin 10	L298N Input
Note: Motor wires must be secured into the L298N screw terminals ("Power Converter") before connecting the jumper wires to the Arduino.

🔧 Assembly & Calibration
Mounting: Secure the Arduino and L298N to the chassis.

Sensor Alignment: Mount IR sensors at the front. Ensure they are at an equal height (approx. 5mm) from the floor.

The "Blue Box" Adjustment: * Place the robot on the white line.

If the green light doesn't turn on, use a small screwdriver to turn the gray screw (potentiometer) on the blue box of the sensor.

Goal: Light should be ON over white and OFF over black.

REMEMBER: THIS FOLLOWS A WHITE LINE NOT A BLACK LINE

  Tips and tricks
You can use a black table for the black surface it will work great!

If you are useing painters tape for the white line use two layers of tape so the ir sencors can read it.

💻 The Code
C++
#include <Servo.h>

// PIN DEFINITIONS
int leftSensor = 2; 
int rightSensor = 3;
int IN1 = 5, IN2 = 6, IN3 = 9, IN4 = 10; 

void setup() {
  pinMode(leftSensor, INPUT);
  pinMode(rightSensor, INPUT);
  pinMode(IN1, OUTPUT); 
  pinMode(IN2, OUTPUT);
  pinMode(IN3, OUTPUT); 
  pinMode(IN4, OUTPUT);
}

void loop() {
  int L = digitalRead(leftSensor);
  int R = digitalRead(rightSensor);

  // LOGIC: White Line Detection (HIGH = White, LOW = Black)
  if (L == LOW && R == LOW) {
    forward(); 
  } 
  else if (L == HIGH && R == LOW) {
    turnLeft(); // Left sensor hit white, adjust left
  } 
  else if (L == LOW && R == HIGH) {
    turnRight(); // Right sensor hit white, adjust right
  } 
  else {
    stopBot(); 
  }
}

void forward() {
  digitalWrite(IN1, HIGH); digitalWrite(IN2, LOW); 
  digitalWrite(IN3, HIGH); digitalWrite(IN4, LOW); 
}

void turnLeft() {
  digitalWrite(IN1, LOW);  digitalWrite(IN2, LOW); 
  digitalWrite(IN3, HIGH); digitalWrite(IN4, LOW); 
}

void turnRight() {
  digitalWrite(IN1, HIGH); digitalWrite(IN2, LOW); 
  digitalWrite(IN3, LOW);  digitalWrite(IN4, LOW); 
}

void stopBot() {
  digitalWrite(IN1, LOW); digitalWrite(IN2, LOW); 
  digitalWrite(IN3, LOW); digitalWrite(IN4, LOW); 
}
⚠️ Troubleshooting
Veering: If the robot drifts, check that both sensors are perfectly level.

Vibration: This code uses digitalWrite (Full Power) to prevent motor jitter common with the Servo library on R4 boards.

Spinning: If the robot spins in circles, swap the two wires of the motor that is spinning backward.

